  <tr id="row_3634" onmouseover="showDiv('CommentBar_3634');" onmouseout="hideDiv('CommentBar_3634')" class="IdeaScale_Comment_Normal">
    <td valign="top" style="padding:3px;">

    <table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
    <tr>
      <td valign="top">
        <div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubtitle">
          <b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/5745-4049">copa</a></b>
          <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">18 hours ago<span>
        </div>
      </td>
      <td valign="top" align="right">
      <div id="CommentBar_3634" style="display:none;">

      
      <span id="FlagComment_3634">
        <a class="iconLink" href="javascript:ajaxLink('FlagComment_3634', '/akira/flagDiscussionComment.do?topicID=3425&commentID=3634')"><img alt="Warning" class="iconLink" src="/images/iconshock/warning_16.gif" border="0">&nbsp;Report Abuse</a>
      </span>
      


            


      </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
    </table>

      


      Currently, 1 out of 8 get less than honorable discharges, most from command decisions not courts martial. 1 out of 3 if you are Black. Racism on the part of the command is the most common reason according to an Army study, not performance. If people are doing the things you worry about they should be discharged and given benefits proportionate to their service time. They will have to list their military job on their resume and they will lack a good reference usually for those reasons. The current DD-214 discharge sheet on the long copy lists written reason for discharge, including homosexual and other punitive ones, a designator code that employers use to discriminate and that is often false information, and a re-enlistment code. People who commit criminal acts or felonies should have a record of that as they would in civilian life. The current system is arbitrary, very hard to appeal, and marks people for life for employment discrimination, which is 60-100% for bad paper. This is a major part of the reason why three times as many veterans and four times as many Black veterans are unemployed as those who never join the military. A civilian job leaves the resume after a few years, not the military service. The other reason for unemployment is lack of training in any marketable skills for civilian life for 90% of veterans. Discharges are used in punitive ways to discipline and threaten people in the military. Bad discharges have only been around since the end of WWII, when "blue discharges" for administrative purposes were established to get homosexuals and dissidents out and punish them. You could be drummed out by courts martial, but that was mostly for serious crimes, save for sodomy. The denial of benefits on this arbitrary basis to so many veterans and marking them for life for trouble getting hired is not commensurate for their infractions against an officious, racist and sexist military authority.

                  
    </td>
  </tr>


